Can the Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when the Swiss voters for a ban on building voted for minarets and the concern about the alleged Islamisation of Europe is widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, a thorough and thoughtful report written about it, whether Muslims in one of the avowedly secular societies can be integrated Europe -- and be integrated.
Some readers of this new book from admiration for the last station of the author: "why the French love no scarves" (original title: "why the French Don't Like Headscarves") (2006) read an elegant and densely argumentierenden study a contentious issue, which divided the country about one and a half decades and employed and whose effects are still visible.
Bowens neustes book offers a more comprehensive and kühneres spectrum.
As a good anthropologist he would like to know not only what the politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what is happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and colleges, which are now the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it "Islamic free" offer.
He is a good listener, he gives debates between teachers and students on the issues that concern them most.
Should marry a Muslim in a mosque or a City Hall (or both)?
Should be lectured young Muslims about evolution and rights of homosexuals?
A Muslim woman can marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim, to use a zinsorientiertes banking system, in order to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly mundane matters, he claims, the daily life, in contrast to the political dramas, the media.
The author acknowledges a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a well-known names, perhaps with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, a born in Switzerland Arabic Muslim scholars and academics.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how it is possible, on the one hand, a good Muslim and, on the other hand, a good citizen in a modern secular society.
They do not have all the arguments on their side.
The Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists interviewed Bowen, are mostly at odds with their Salafi counterparts – supporters of the puristischen Sunni Islam with Saudi Arabia in – nowadays a small but influential presence among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen is of the opinion that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires a give and take on both sides.
He is questioning whether French political leaders (and the intellectual elite, so passionate the separation of church and state watches) really committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may be a rougher treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews, which in turn had to make their historic compromise with the secular republicanism.
He sees more of a "tightening of values" as a growing pragmatism.
The Islam can be French? After reading this book, one is inclined to say "yes, but not yet."
The trostloseste outlook of the world
The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatic than any other environmental region on Earth.
The ice is melting at an alarming rate and takes life that can survive anywhere else.
Oil, gas, schifffahrts- and fishing interests in the newly open water, with diplomats, lawyers, and now also authors in their wake.
Richard Ellis, an author and Illustrator, in "on thin ice" (original title: "on Thin Ice"), a natural history of the icon of the North, the polar bears.
familiar in the complex history and politics of the whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arktiser researchers who have proved themselves in the hunt for the polar bears.
Admiral Nelsons encounter with a polar bears as a brave 14-year-old Fähnrich sea, only with the rifle musket-shape fought, is certainly a myth, but others are true.
