Ironically, in the waters in the north of this two hunting nations the ice longest remain.
In his new book "After the ice" (original title "After the ICE") offers Alun Anderson, a former editor of Science magazine "New Scientist," a clear and disturbing description of the science of the Arctic and a packenden insight into how the future could develop.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheres scientists still Ozeanografen can adequately explain the speed of change.
