UN group plan to reduce emissions
The by the United Nations-sponsored conference on climate change -- until now by wild posturing and mutual accusations had -- on Friday with the publication of a document, a priority for the next 40 years, recording an ambitious reduction of greenhouse gases, the industrialised nations in the near future would have to shoulder the biggest burden.
The text, which is the basis for a final political agreement on the regulation of greenhouse gases could provide, has both the remaining obstacles, as also shown the way forward.
But he was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation, the time next week, more than 100 leaders from around the world will arrive in Copenhagen.
The text, which was created by a special UN working group has been formulated, is silent on the amount of money from the rich countries to poor countries should be short and long term, so that they can deal with global warming.
He also offers a range of options for the key issues, including how industrial and big emerging countries can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of the global temperature should be, the political decision-makers.
The process will be given a great deal of flexibility, so John Coequyt, a senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who has six pages of the document, has drafted a 180 pages long negotiating text, with the focus on what the leading climate representative of the UN, Yvo de Boer, as "the big picture."
It shows the outline of a possible agreement, in which the industrial nations together their emissions by 2020 to 25 to 45 percent, compared with the levels of 1990, would cut, while major developing countries were to reduce their emissions in the same period of 15 to 30 percent.
Together the countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European community has the talks on Friday a boost by their assurance, over the next three years, 3.6 billion dollars per year, in order to help poorer countries to adapt to the effects of climate change - from maestros of floods and droughts by avoiding deforestation.
The Friday expressed the same verbal fireworks, what the talks in the last week.
