Stern issued its opinion one hour after the declaration of the Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei, which meant that it feels the leading US climate negotiator either of "common sense" or "highly irresponsible" of him was that he said earlier this week that the United States, China would not help financially to tackle global warming.
The fact that the future economic direction of the major world powers is at stake, both within the industrial nations, as well as between the industrialized nations and emerging countries opened up fault lines.
The current fight applies equally to the rescue of individual economies, as well as to save the planet, with China and the United States because of their respective commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder steps.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the major powers to fight, who bear the costs of slowing down of the greenhouse gas emissions, because even affected countries have begun to act more aggressively, the countries with very high greenhouse gas levy for their deeds to account.
It is clear that this is a game, which will develop a new economic domination, Ulate, who is also a regional climate change adviser for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries that are most exposed to the impact of climate change, said that they continue to a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen would fight, although the leading participants say that the talks in the best case scenario will lead to a political agreement.
The alliance of small island states with 43 members on early Friday morning presented a 24 page draft treaty.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive of the small island states, "exerting political pressure on the entire political process," in part because they are now united and measures of the emerging countries such as China and India.
The talks got a new urgency as the delegates focused on the fact that most of the open questions before the arrival of the government leaders must be resolved in order to reach an agreement.
