United States: tomb record in Zola, estimated at 1.5 million U.S. dollars
A Roman grabplatte, which the French writer Emile Zola, was on Thursday to 1.5 million dollars on their value, so the dealers Sotheby 's.
This record is two metres long and 63 cm high. It comes from the Third century after Christ and was priced with 150,000 to 250,000 dollars.
The marble on the "four scenes of Dionysus portrayed in a sophistischen architecture decorative, surrounded by Satyren and Bacchus characters, is a rare piece. There are in the world, only four or five of them," said Florent Heintz, Vice President for auction Roman and Egyptian antiques at Sotheby's on Tuesday to the AFP.
It was sold under hundreds of pieces.
"The sale is ongoing, but this part is certainly what the buyers so far have provided the most," says the spokesman of Sotheby's, Dan Abernethy to the AFP.
The discovery of this acquisition of marble part by Emile Zola goes far back.
The record was almost 300 years in Rome in the famous collection of the Borghese family at home, then they cropped up bit by bit in the French actress Cécile Sorel, who was found in her bathing rooms of their Paris hotels for use and Paul Reynaud, a minister in the Third French Republic and President of the Council before Marshal Pétain came to power.
The next 50 years are in the dark.
When the database of the Louvre Florent Heintz discovered that this record part of a "heritage of Emile Zola" was the 1903, a year after the death of the author of "Thérèse Raquin" and the Fresko "Rougon-Macquart", was opened.
