Drivers: three marathons for an agreement that secures the supply of Christmas
After three weeks of negotiating marathon came the unions of road Association and the TLF - the only employers' organisation, which remained until the end - on Friday evening to an agreement, the strike order and the threat of severe supply bottleneck at Christmas to an end.
At the signature sitting on Friday evening "welcomed" the secretary of state for transport, Dominique Bussereau the agreement, which was launched on Wednesday morning after several weeks of negotiations.
After a second night of divided the negotiating on early Friday morning in the hope that the agreement at the end of the morning to sign quickly.
And despite the fact that the three employers' associations (FNTR, Unostra and OTRE) leave the meeting.
However, it has taken more than six hours from the start of the meeting at 11: 00 a.m. until the conclusion of the agreement and only about 18: 00 p.m. the agreement was signed.
The conflict "should the company very much harm" and "it was to be feared that it would affect the holidays at the end of the year," Bussereau.
The agreement provides for a wage increase of 4% for the lowest wages (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest wage groups (international transport).
The hourly rate for workers with the lowest wages rising from 8.72 euros to 9.06 euros.
"It is not very much, but we are starting once small", as Mr Clos (FO).
The activists are now instructed not to block supply centers.
"There will probably always be some recalcitrant, are not satisfied with the agreement," he added.
The TLF-Chairman Philippe Grillot spoke of a "good agreement", although it was "difficult to give these wage increases in the face of international competition".
According to him, the increase in 170 euros a month for the low and 100 to 120 euros for the high wages.
"This agreement is based on the common sense and respect for the employees," maxim Dumont (CFDT), whereas Thierry Douine (CFTC) of a "historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) spoke on this matter, "an acceptable compromise."
The agreement also provides for the increase of travel expenses by 3% and the objectives of the overall budget for road transport in the first half of 2010, which will enable it, in particular, the issue of 13 monthly salary and the modernisation of collective agreements.
M. Bussereau recalled that "the sinking of the charges for employers to the tune of EUR 100 million," the subject of an amendment to the government on the draft of the amended finances for 2009, which was on the night of Thursday to Friday, was adopted by the National Assembly.
The government calls "an identical" vote by the Senate.
The signature of the TLF allows that the agreement for the first on this organisation affiliated companies, and then in the event of an extension through the labour minister for the entire profession.
This will be the case "in a very short period of time," Bussereau insured.
The opposition of the employers' associations can only delay the process.
The Association of FNTR lambasted a "fraudulent trade ", because the 100 million euro" were the sector to offset some of the carbon tax has already been promised ".
The Secretary of State for transport forced us to negotiate as soon as possible, but not on the basis of a joint analysis, but to avoid disgruntling the goose eaters to the approaching Christmas days, laments the Unostra.
For the association Otre threatens the agreement "small and medium-sized companies in the sector over the next 12 months, a great digging."
