Turkish Constitutional Court resolves pro-Kurdish party. Decision with serious consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court on Friday was the dissolution of the pro-Kurdish main party in the country known; a decision that immediate angry demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision threatens to complicate the work of the government, which is trying to reach out to the Kurdish community, in order to make the last 25 years of conflict to an end.
The "party for a democratic society" (DTP) was dissolved, because they had become a "haven for activities that for the independence of the state and its indivisible unity are bad," the President of the Constitutional Court Hasim Kiliç four days after the decision to the press.
According to Kiliç the decision would be taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes would have been required to impose the dissolution. Moreover, he pointed out that 37 of the leadership of the party, including the chairman Ahmet Türk and parliamentarian Aysel Tugluk, for a period of five years have been excluded from the political scene.
Furthermore, the judge announced the lifting of parliamentary immunity, the Türk Tugluk and enjoy, and the seizure of assets of the party.
The DTP now has 21 seats in Parliament (550).
The Parteiführenden spoke before the verdict that the Members of Parliament would leave rather than party of parliamentarians to meet.
The decision followed a in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Turkish federal court Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya proceedings. he accused the DTP, which "command" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which Ankara and many other countries as a terrorist organisation.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase the PKK rebels.
The party is assured, "no link" to the PKK, but refuses to describe this as a terrorist organisation, and calls on the government to negotiate.
The verdict of the Constitutional Court funkt the government intervened, anxious to accommodate the Kurdish community and a number of measures to strengthen the rights of the Kurds to support the PKK, the Kurds are drying up and put an end to the conflict.
The leaders of the DTP confirm that a dissolution of a outbreak of tensions in the southeast Anatolia could lead, where numerous demonstrations against the conditions of detention of the PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan in recent weeks led to clashes with the police.
Since the announcement of the Court gathered thousands of demonstrators outside the premises of the DTP in the millions of city of Diyarbakir in the south-east, mostly populated by Kurds.
The forces of law and order, tear gas grenades and water cannons, when the demonstrators began to throw Molotov cocktails and stones.
Hundreds of people also marched in Istanbul.
After the verdict was Türk, that the decision of the court "further deepen the despair ".
"Turkey can clarify these (Kurdish, Mr editorial) issue not on the basis of the ban of a party," he told the press.
The government, consisting of a party that has emerged from the Islamist movement, regretted the decision.
"We oppose in principle against the closure of the parties.
That does not solve the problems, "Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
"This decision is a frustrating the democratic opening, which was promoted by the government," the political market observers Ahmet island.
"you can obviously for a reaction from the PKK," he added.
On Thursday, the PKK to an attack, in which three days earlier killed seven soldiers in the north of Turkey. It was one of the most brutal attacks over the past few months.
New Silicon Valley
For many years it was a secret city, for Western visitors inaccessible.
Selenograd, one in ten districts of the capital, Moscow, was in the Soviet Union, a strict bewachter location for secret defence research.
Today, the community with its 216 000 inhabitants, 37 miles from the Moscow Centre away, as "Russian Silicon Valley".
Major research and production facilities for micro and nano electronics are here.
Since September 2008, representatives Selenograds contacts to Frankfurt science location Riedberg - with the Uniinstituten and the firms of Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There have been several mutual visits and signed on Wednesday now Selenograd and Riedberg in Frankfurt a "protocol on closer cooperation."
The Moscow Deputy Mayor Yuri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smirnov of Selenograd led the Russian delegation, signed up for Frankfurt Planungsdezernent Edwin Black.
2010 will be representatives of the FIZ and small and medium-sized enterprises in the scientific Foschungsschwerpunkts for a seminar after Selenograd.
Scientific exchanges
It is a continuous scientific exchanges.
But it is also about economic relations.
Firms of the FIZ will be on the growing Russian market.
Conversely, want to Russian science firms contracts in Germany.
Selenograd is the seat of major Russian research institutes and companies.
These include the Moscow Institute for electron technology, the big corporations Sitronics and Rosssijskaja Elektronika.
The town hall was in 1958 as a so-called "socialist plan city" for the defence research has been established.
Selenograd (literally translated as "green city") got its name from the forested hills landscape, in which the research institutes are embedded.
Stuttgart brake
The dimension of Stuttgart 21 cannot be set high enough.
For the supporters of the project is purely and simply, "the new heart of Europe".
Law. S21 is much more than the Tiefer of a railway station, more than a gigantic construction project, which is the City of Baden-Württemberg provincial capital for a decade in shambles construction sites chaos.
Stuttgart 21 is from the spirit of the 1980's.
Head stations with tracks that end up in the middle of the city, were at that time as transport technical fossils of the 19th century, as disengage a modern rail transport, as it once was a huge amount of time needed, locomotives from behind umzuspannen forward.
Harvest, keep briefly to go further - so ´ s should go.
And that is why the head stations disappear: in Frankfurt and Munich.
And in Stuttgart: a durchfahrtsbahnhof the rules half-way through the trans-European schienen-magistrale between Paris and Budapest / Bratislava - hence the slogan of the "heart of Europe".
S21 will now actually addressed, although the visions of the 1980s no longer compatible with the reality.
Even very ambitious planners have realised that it is in the hessischen and the Bavarian city almost unaffordable to implement the Tiefer.
Head stations have also, however, no entry and exit problem anymore, since there are modern turning trains with locomotives and tax cars at both ends.
Nevertheless, Stuttgart 21 and the new route after Ulm is now being addressed.
Regional and local politicians have enforced.
The train with power, partly because the risks of the largest infrastructure bears-Einzelprojekts the Republic of taxpayers and not the state corporation.
Städtebaulich is the project is still reasonably justified.
There is new stadtraum, is the computergenerierten graphics of the planners - with a lot of green.
For the transport system rail is S21 harmful.
The transit station and the routes expansion are intended for passenger transport, which - typical 1980s - imposed huge growth.
At that time, there was not the competition from low-cost carriers.
Modern transport policy, but it must first go to strengthen the freight transport, because the transport by rail is much cleaner than by lorries on the roads.
But the new route because of intense climbs, not for freight trains.
Much more serious that S21 indirectly affects many other rail projects.
Good six billion euros in schwäbischen are buried.
That is the official number.
Experts believe that ten to 15 billion for realistic.
It is clear that in the next decade will be the money to other hubs and Engstellen in the network.
A total of 60 major projects are on the list of the Ministry.
One of the most important is the development of the 180 km route through the Rhine valley.
Since 1987, is being built on the route in slow motion.
So desperately needed, right here on the tube.
But S21 will act as a brake.
The Rheintal route is the real bottleneck for international freight transport: right in the heart of Europe.
